This  project concerns the interplay between quantum field theory and  cosmology. A central prediction of the former is that the fields at each point in space experience an irreducible amount of jitter, whereas the latter predicts that the very early universe underwent a phase of accelerated expansion at an extremely rapid rate. Combining quantum field theory with cosmology implies that the quantum jitter of certain fields builds up to have a noticeable effect on how particles propagate, on electromagnetic and gravitational forces, and on the expansion of the universe. The PI studied these effects with collaborators from North America, Europe and Asia. Principal results were:

A systematic technique of controlled approximations for representing the field strengths of quantum fluctuations in the geometry of an expanding universe;
A technique for representing the late time impact of quantum effects from the very early universe;
Development of techniques for distinguishing real effects from artifacts of the coordinate system;

Demonstration that quantum fluctuations in gravity increase the intensity of light as it propagates, and also increase the strength of electromagentic forces;
Demonstration that quantum fluctuations in the simplest type of matter decrease the strength of gravity;
Demonstration that quantum fluctuations from ordinary matter change the expansion of the universe by a large amount; and
Constraints on fundamental theory from the simultaneous detection of optical and gravitational radiation from neutron star mergers.





This project also promoted education and training. Three Ph.D students were graduated during the project. Two of these already hold American STEM jobs in education and the military. The most recent graduate is set to assume a STEM position in the fall, also inside the United States. Although the PI's graduate students were chosen soley on the basis of ability and training it is worth noting that 60% of his graduates have been Hispanic or female.


